		<td><b>TLROM board question</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Simple question and almost sure about the answer but I just want to confirm it.
<br />
<br />TLROM board can support up to 512K of prg-rom, which I read from the wiki. If the original game contains a 28 pins 128k and you swap it for a 512k one with the right wiring, I guess it would work.  Is my assumption correct?
<br />
<br />The reason I asked this question is because in a previous thread, people where talking about NROM-128/256 and it got me worry that my future donor cart would not support what I want to do with it.
<br />
<br />I guess this thread will only have one answer and it will be over. Thanks for the information and sorry for asking such a simple question. I just want to remove doubts in my mind.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tokumaru</b> [ Mon Nov 03, 2008 5:55 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Although some T*ROM boards use 28-pin ROMs, they still have he extra 4 holes to support 32-pin ROMs.
<br />
<br />In the boards I tested, the 4 extra holes were correctly wired to support 32-pin chips, but I seem to remember someone saying that there were boards where this wasn't the case. I've never seen one of these though.
<br />
<br />So the answer to your question is: T*ROM boards were probably designed to support both 28-pin and 32-pin ROMs without modifications, meaning you could turn them into dev carts without worrying, but since once someone said that there were different boards, you'd better check how the 4 extra holes are connected in yours using a multimeter or some other tool that checks connections. I'd say you have a 99% chance of the board being prepared for the larger chips, but you can never be too careful.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


